{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539804"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:46:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:46:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16704"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16704"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.35,0.13,0.14,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9395"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105024"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9395"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16704"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87413"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"3879"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4559"},{"type":"tags","id":"4815"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22213"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35086"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43642"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105024"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Sexual Health clinic with a three-week history of painless genital ulcers. She has recently returned from working in Papua New Guinea. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She reports having unprotected sexual intercourse with a new partner two months ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are several beefy-red, granular ulcers on her labia that bleed easily when touched. The ulcers are not painful. There is no inguinal lymphadenopathy. The rest of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary syphilis","Donovanosis","Chancroid","Lymphogranuloma venereum","Herpes simplex infection"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with characteristic features of donovanosis (granuloma inguinale), caused by the bacterium \u003Cem\u003EKlebsiella granulomatis\u003C/em\u003E. The painless, beefy-red, granular ulcers that bleed easily on contact are typical. The disease is endemic in Papua New Guinea, making the travel history particularly relevant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDonovanosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents after an incubation period of 1-12 weeks with painless, progressive ulceration. The diagnosis can be confirmed by visualising characteristic Donovan bodies (intracellular bacteria) on tissue smear or biopsy. Treatment is with azithromycin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary syphilis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a single, painless, clean-based ulcer (chancre) with firm, rolled edges. The ulcer is typically accompanied by regional lymphadenopathy, which is absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex infection\u003C/strong\u003E presents with painful vesicles that rupture to form shallow ulcers. The lesions are typically painful and accompanied by systemic symptoms during primary infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphogranuloma venereum\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E serovars L1-L3, typically presents with a small, painless papule that may ulcerate, followed by painful inguinal lymphadenopathy. The absence of lymphadenopathy makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChancroid\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus ducreyi\u003C/em\u003E, presents with painful, purulent ulcers with undermined edges and painful lymphadenopathy. The painless nature of the ulcers in this case makes chancroid unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Donovanosis (granuloma inguinale) presents with painless, beefy-red ulcers that gradually enlarge and spread.","Diagnosis of donovanosis is confirmed by visualising characteristic Donovan bodies on tissue smear or biopsy.","Azithromycin is the first-line treatment for donovanosis, with clinical improvement expected within days."],"references":["Australian STI Management Guidelines. Donovanosis [Internet]. [cited 2024 Nov 29]. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/donovanosis/","O\u0027Farrell N. Donovanosis. Sex Transm Infect. 2002 Dec;78(6):452-7. doi: 10.1136/sti.78.6.452. PMID: 12473810; PMCID: PMC1758360."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87413"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16704"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87413"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-06T16:33:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-06T16:34:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9395"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105024"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22